features.text:
Samantha Sklar 

Storytelling, no matter the medium, is crucial my to creativity. Often, I write in vignettes or paint in the abstract as a way to suggest rather than to reveal. The stories, though they may be told from the perspectives of fictional characters or with obscure shapes, are all authentic to my soul. I crave authenticity. I cannot create what I do not feel, nor can I pretend to feel a certain way. My inspiration is often fickle and, more than enough, I am looking for it rather than basking in it.

My mother used to hear me sing from the baby monitor and then when I learned to speak, but could not yet write, I would dictate stories to her. I studied classical vocals for twelve years, competing in state competitions and participating in various select choirs. I graduated from Purchase College in May 2020, where I chose to pursue the humanities rather than the arts as a way to stoke a more intellectual sense of creativity. I received a degree in history with a concentration in Jewish studies. I wrote, recorded, and independently released three albums during my time at Purchase: Florá, Evergreen, and Not Every Garden Is Eden.

Evergreen is a track of the album "Evergreen," an album of imperfect demos with some harmony inspired by John Denver, Townes Van Zandt, and Bruce Springsteen. The album was released in 2019 while Samantha was still studying at Purchase College. Samantha decided to try something new by entering into the NFT space and utilizing her MoonRunner NFT (#4123) for the music video.

Artist: Samantha Sklar

STREETS OF BROOKLYN (Life After The Pandemic)
---

The Streets of Brooklyn Heights & DUMBO  is the second photography documentary project in our new series, “Life After The Pandemic.” Our goal is to explore various areas of New York: capturing the culture around it, as well as examine the effects of the pandemic.

What’s Your Story?
